Detecting Pneumonia with Deep Learning¶

In this notebook I tackle the computer vision task of detecting pneumonia from x-ray images of lungs using deep learning. The data consists of 5856 x-ray images taken from normally functioning lungs and lungs with pneumonia. The approach is to train a binary classifier that given an x-ray image, predicts either 0 or 1 corresponding to whether the patient has pneumonia or not. The data is acquired from Kaggle.

First, let's load the libraries used:

Data Input¶

I define a function for reading the data from local memory. The data is pre-divded into training, validation and testing sets. The directory structure for the data is as follows:

The function reads the images from all directories into the preffered size using the cv2 library. It returns a tuple containing the images and labels (0 for normal, 1 for pneumonia) stored as numpy arrays for each data subset. The function also preprocesses the images by rescaling the color channel values from 0:255 to 0:1.

In [2]:
IMG_SIZE = 256
def read_data(root_dir, img_size = IMG_SIZE):
    train_x = []
    train_y = []
    test_x = []
    test_y = []
    val_x = []
    val_y = []
    for dataset in ["test", "train", "val"]:
        for labelint, label in enumerate(["Normal", "Pneumonia"]):
            dirpath = os.path.join(root_dir, dataset, label)
            for img in os.listdir(dirpath):
                curimg = cv2.imread(os.path.join(dirpath, img), cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)
                curimg = cv2.resize(curimg, (img_size, img_size))
                curimg = curimg/255
                if(dataset == "test"):
                    test_x.append(curimg)
                    test_y.append(labelint)
                elif(dataset == "train"):
                    train_x.append(curimg)
                    train_y.append(labelint)
                else:
                    val_x.append(curimg)
                    val_y.append(labelint)
    train_x = np.array(train_x).reshape(-1, img_size, img_size, 1)
    train_y = np.array(train_y)
    test_x = np.array(test_x).reshape(-1, img_size, img_size, 1)
    test_y = np.array(test_y)
    val_x = np.array(val_x).reshape(-1, img_size, img_size, 1)
    val_y = np.array(val_y)
    return((train_x, train_y, test_x, test_y, val_x, val_y))

A single example stored in a numpy array is of shape (img_size, img_size, 1)

Preprocessing¶

By plotting the observations of the default data subsets, we can notice that the division is quite imbalanced. For one, there are only 16 examples in the validation set and also the proportion of the classes of images are quite uneven.

In [5]:
def countBarPlot(train_y, val_y, test_y):
    train_counts = np.unique(train_y, return_counts = True)[1]
    test_counts = np.unique(test_y, return_counts = True)[1]
    val_counts = np.unique(val_y, return_counts = True)[1]
    normal_counts = [x[0] for x in (train_counts, test_counts, val_counts)]
    pneum_counts = [x[1] for x in (train_counts, test_counts, val_counts)]
    x = np.arange(3)
    width = 0.4
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,2)
    rect1 = axs[0].bar(x-width/2, pneum_counts, width = width, label = "Pneumonia")
    rect2 = axs[0].bar(x+width/2, normal_counts, width = width, label = "Normal")
    
    def autolabel(rects, ax, xoffset = 0, yoffset = 3, formatstr = "{height:.0f}"):
        for rect in rects:
            height = rect.get_height()
            ax.annotate(formatstr.format(height = height),
                        xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height + rect.get_y()),
                        xytext=(xoffset, yoffset),
                        textcoords="offset points",
                        ha='center', va='bottom')
    autolabel(rect1, axs[0])
    autolabel(rect2, axs[0])
    axs[0].set_ylim([0, max(max((pneum_counts, normal_counts))) * 1.25])
    axs[0].set_xticks(x)
    axs[0].set_xticklabels(["Train", "Test", "Val"])
    axs[0].set_ylabel("f")
    train_p = train_counts/len(train_y) * 100
    test_p = test_counts/len(test_y) * 100
    val_p = val_counts/len(val_y) * 100
    
    normal_p = [x[0] for x in (train_p, test_p, val_p)]
    pneum_p = [x[1] for x in (train_p, test_p, val_p)]
    
    rects3 = axs[1].bar(x, pneum_p, label = "Pneumonia", width = 2*width)
    rects4 = axs[1].bar(x, normal_p, bottom = pneum_p, label = "Normal", width = 2*width)
    axs[1].set_xticks(x)
    axs[1].set_xticklabels(["Train", "Test", "Val"])
    axs[1].set_ylabel("%")
    
    autolabel(rects3, axs[1], 0, -15, "{height:.1f} %")
    autolabel(rects4, axs[1], 0, -15, "{height:.1f} %")
    handles, labels = axs[1].get_legend_handles_labels()
    fig.legend(handles, labels, loc='upper center')   
    fig.set_size_inches(10,5)
countBarPlot(train_y, val_y, test_y)

I redefine the train-val-test split for the dataset using a 0.8 - 0.1 - 0.1 split. This results in having 4684 training examples and 586 validation and testing examples. We also obtain a much more balanced class distribution between the sets.

Data Augmentation¶

I use data augmentation to prevent overfitting and maximize generalization. The training set images are randomly flipped, zoomed, panned, sheared and rotated to create a more versatile training set. The data augmentation is implemented with a generator at training time, and thus the model has a really small probability to process exactly the same training example twice. Some augmented training examples are printed below with their labels.

In [7]:
data_augm = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip = True, zoom_range = 0.1, rotation_range = 10,
        width_shift_range=0.1,  
        height_shift_range=0.1, shear_range = 0.1)

Model Building¶

The goal is to build and train feasable sized neural network that detects pneumonia from the images. The problem boils down to a binary image recognition task, where the neural network gets an image as an input and outputs a real number between 0 and 1 corresponding to the confidence the model has of the input image belonging to class "Pneumonia". The neural network attempts to find the parameters that minimize the binary crossentropy cost defined as: \begin{equation} \sum_{i=1}^n y_i\log{p_i} + (1-y_i)\log(1-p_i) \end{equation} for the $n$ predictions $p$ and true class labels $y$ (0 for normal, 1 for pneumonia).

Linear Classifier¶

I use a linear classifier, namely logistic regression to define a baseline for model performance. The linear classifier has 65537 parameters, one for each pixel value and one bias term. It calculates the prediction \begin{equation} p = \textrm{sigmoid}(\sum_{i=1}^{65536} (w_ix_i) + b) \end{equation} where $x_i$ are the pixel values. The adaptive moments estimation algorithm with learning rate 1e-5 is used for optimization. Early stopping of training is used for the validation loss to prevent overfitting and excessively long training. The classification accuracy is also monitored.

In [8]:
linear_classifier = models.Sequential()

linear_classifier.build(train_x.shape)

Convolutional Network¶

Next, I build the convolutional neural network architecture. It uses four convolutional layers with max-pooling followed by a densely connected layer with 32 nodes. The last layer uses the sigmoid activation function where as the others use ReLU. In total, the model has 535 257 parameters. The optimization algorithm is the same as with the linear classifier with a bit larger learning rate. The model is trained for 150 epochs, with a batch size of 128. I again use early stopping on validation loss select the best model.

In [12]:
cnn = models.Sequential()

cnn.add(layers.Conv2D(filters = 8, kernel_size = 2, strides = 1, padding = "same"))
cnn.add(layers.ReLU())
cnn.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2), 2, "valid"))
cnn.add(layers.Conv2D(filters = 16, kernel_size = 2, strides = 1, padding = "same"))
cnn.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2), 2, "valid"))
cnn.add(layers.ReLU())
cnn.add(layers.Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = 2, strides = 1, padding = "same"))
cnn.add(layers.ReLU())
cnn.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2), 2, "valid"))
cnn.add(layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = 2, strides = 1, padding = "same"))
cnn.add(layers.ReLU())
cnn.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2), 2, "valid"))
cnn.add(layers.Flatten())
cnn.add(layers.Dense(32))
cnn.add(layers.ReLU())
cnn.add(layers.Dense(1, activation = K.activations.sigmoid))

cnn.compile(loss = "binary_crossentropy", optimizer = K.optimizers.Adam(1e-4), metrics=['acc'])
cnn.build(train_x.shape)

Validation¶

Next, I test how the model performs on the test validation set in more detail. Often the most important metric for binary classification is the prediction accuracy, that is the proportion of correctly classified test units. Since the model predictions output what can be thought of as probabilities, some cutoff value needs to be decided to arrive at a class prediction. The default value for the keras accuracy metric is 0.5 and here the prediction accuracy is the above mentioned 0.9454.

Here are the predicted probabilities for the misclassified test cases at cutoff 0.5. We can see that although there are quite many gross misclassifications, there are also a few "close calls". Adjusting the cutoff value might change the results.

In a clinical setup we often want a test to have a high recall (or true positive rate), even if it leads to a lower specificity (false positive rate). It is more dangerous for a clinical test to miss an actual infection than to generate some false alarms. Precision (rate of true positives in all positives) is also an important measure and often the goal is to find a good balance of precision and recall. Precision can be translated into "the probability that the subject has pneumonia given that the model detected pneumonia". The harmonic mean of precision and recall is often used to aggregate the two measures, and is also known as the $F_1$ score.

\begin{equation} F_1 = \frac{2}{\frac{1}{\textrm{precision}} + \frac{1}{\textrm{recall}}} \end{equation}

A way of visualizing sensitivity and specificity at different cut of values is by plotting the receiver operating characteristic curve. The area under the ROC curve is a good indication for model performance, especially when the predicted classes are well balanced in the test set. It ranges from 0 to 1 where a naive classifier gets a score of 0.5. The ROC curve for the linear classifier is also plotted for reference.

Next, I plot the $F_1$ scores, precisions and recall scores to find the optimum value of cutoff in the validation set.

In [26]:
f1_scores = []
precisions = []
recalls = []
cutoffs = np.arange(0, 1, 0.01)
for cutoff in cutoffs:
    f1 = metrics.f1_score(val_y, preds > cutoff)
    f1_scores.append(f1)
    precision = metrics.precision_score(val_y, preds > cutoff)
    recall = metrics.recall_score(val_y, preds > cutoff)
    precisions.append(precision)
    recalls.append(recall)
f1_scores = np.array(f1_scores)
precisions = np.array(precisions)
recalls = np.array(recalls)
plt.plot(cutoffs, f1_scores, label = "f1")
plt.plot(cutoffs, precisions, label = "precision")
plt.plot(cutoffs, recalls, label = "recall")
plt.legend()
plt.ylabel("value")
plt.xlabel("cutoff")
plt.gcf().set_size_inches(15,10)

We can now select the best cutoff value for any optimality criterion. One such criterion could be the maximum $F_1$ score achieved. In this medical context a better criterion could be to those a cutoff value that achieves some predetermined level of recall, such as 0.99. Then we would have a model which detects 0.99 percent of pneumonia cases and generates the minimun amount of false positives.

In [45]:
RECALL_BOUND = 0.985
print("Highest F1 score:", "{0:.3f}".format(np.max(f1_scores)), "at cutoff:", "{0:.2f}".format(cutoffs[np.argmax(f1_scores)]))
print("Precision at recall", str(RECALL_BOUND) + ":", "{0:.3f}".format(np.max(precisions[recalls > RECALL_BOUND])), "at cutoff:",  "{0:.2f}".format(cutoffs[recalls > RECALL_BOUND][np.argmax(precisions[recalls > RECALL_BOUND])]))
